Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Bank PHB, Uchumi, Afribank Nigeria Are Active

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-05-31T18:07:05Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-31/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-uchumi-east-african-breweries-move.html
Kenya’s All-Share Index slumped 2.5
percent to 73.12 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi, the lowest
since March 31.  Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  increased 0.9 percent
to 868.56 by the 4 p.m. end of trading in Windhoek, the highest
close since April 29. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share
Index advanced for the third day, gaining 0.1 percent to
25,866.62 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to an e-
mail from the bourse. The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index
slipped less than 0.1 percent to 1,162.01 by the 3 p.m. close in
Accra, the lowest since May 13. Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index rose
less than 0.1 percent to 2,078.95 by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port
Louis.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Bank PHB Plc (PLATINUM)  , a Nigerian lender bailed out
two years ago by the  central bank , fell 6 kobo, or 4.9 percent,
to 1.16 naira, the weakest since May 4. The Central Bank of
 Nigeria  will withdraw interbank guarantees for any bailed out
lender that fails to meet a Sept. 30 deadline to recapitalize,
the Guardian newspaper cited Governor Lamido Sanusi as saying.
 Finbank Plc (FIRSTINL)  , retreated 2 kobo, or 3 percent, to 65
kobo.  Afribank Nigeria Plc (AFRIBANK)  , dropped 8 kobo, or 4.8
percent, to 1.60 naira.  Oceanic Bank International Plc (OCEANIC)   decreased 1 kobo, or 0.6 percent, to 1.76 naira.  East African Breweries Ltd. (EABL)  , Diageo Plc’s Kenyan
unit and the nation’s largest liquor maker, climbed 1 shilling,
or 0.5 percent, to 209 shillings, its highest price since May
10, after a Kenyan court suspended the start of an anti-liquor
law.  Uchumi Supermarket Ltd. (UCSP)  , a Kenyan retailer that
emerged from bankruptcy, slumped as much as 26 percent, before
closing down 2 shillings, or 14 percent, to 12.5 shillings. The
shares last traded on May 31, 2006, at 14.50 shillings,
according to Bloomberg data.  “There are investors who have been holding the shares for
a long time and want to unlock some money,” Victor Odendo, an
investment manager at Nairobi-based CIC Asset Management Ltd.,
said in a phone interview today. “The biggest beneficiaries are
the debenture holders who got in at 10 shillings and are
unlocking value.”  To contact the reporter on this story:
